metadata.name: Noisy Gardens #120
metadata.description:
I had a wonderful childhood. I grew up near a big lake, in a house with a huge garden. You could get lost for the whole day, building houses on trees, collecting flowers and stones or stealing food from the vegetable garden. Having a brother of the same age made things even better, endless adventures with somebody saving you every time you are too dumb to realize you are walking into troubles.

We enjoyed the summers with the hot days, the fireflies and the nights full of falling stars. The winters with the snow, the stalactites and our box turtle disappearing for months to then reappear in the spring (Until she did not).

At the same time, taking care of the garden was a big responsibility, affecting our family life in many ways. Numerous times, I felt like the efforts we were putting in to keep it in order were never enough and nature was always faster in restoring her point of view. A struggle that affects us humans since we started to bend nature at our will, thousands of years ago.

In my gardens, I tried to capture this struggle, this constant fight to shape nature at our will.
However, I also tried to represent the beauty that can be found in both savage and human shaped nature, if shaped with love and respect.

I dedicate this project to my grandfather, who gave us a garden.
I am sure he would have loved it.

---

Hand coded with love and obsession. ðŸ’š

Powered by p5, p5.createLoop and chroma.

======> COMMANDS (In Live Mode) <======

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save the current output.
Press â€˜mâ€™ to open a menu with the available outputs.

The generation of a hi-res image, up to 8000x8000, takes a few seconds.
The generation of an Animated GIF takes several minutes and the save command works only once the GIF is complete.

Settings are passed as URL parameters that can be used to load different configurations.

- mode = 0 | 1
0 For static PNG images, 1 for animated GIFs

- size = s | m | l
The Size of the output, 1080x1080, 4000x4000, 8000x8000 for static images and 512x512, 800x800, 1080x1080 for animated GIFs

- fps = 10 | 15 | 20 | 25 | 30
Frames per second of animated GIFs

metadata.name: Variations #115
metadata.description:
Thousands of rectangles of 8 different colors are positioned on the screen, each color following its own pattern.

By doing so they form shapes that are similar in some aspects, different in others, and together create a larger pattern. Sometimes these shapes are grouped to form another pattern at an intermediate level.

Each iteration, once minted, will also become part of a larger whole that is the generative piece.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 3200Ã—3200.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=5000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #164
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to â€œlush, greenâ€ and Brut means â€œdry, raw, or unrefined.â€

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growthâ€¦ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÌˆm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
â€˜Sâ€™ : save as png (2376â€ŠÃ—â€Š3360)
â€™Vâ€™ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
â€˜g=nâ€™ : no grain
â€˜g=pâ€™ : paper grain
â€˜h=tâ€™ : high resolution mode, 5940â€ŠÃ—â€Š8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append â€œ&g=p&h=tâ€ to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.
